of life years saved by an intervention","Total healthcare costs divided by years of life gained","Sum of disease-free years after treatment"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EQuality-adjusted life years are calculated using a simple formula: \u003Cstrong\u003Elength of life multiplied by a quality of life score\u003C/strong\u003E. The quality of life score ranges from 0 (death) to 1 (perfect health). For example, if someone lives for 2 years with a quality of life score of 0.5, this equals 1 QALY.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETotal healthcare costs divided by years of life gained\u003C/strong\u003E describes cost per life year gained, a different health economic measure. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENumber of life years saved by an intervention\u003C/strong\u003E only considers survival duration without accounting for quality of life. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQuality of life score minus years with disability\u003C/strong\u003E would not give a meaningful QALY value. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESum of disease-free years after treatment\u003C/strong\u003E fails to account for varying quality of life states during periods of illness. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EQALYs are essential for cost-utility analysis and help healthcare systems make decisions about resource allocation by comparing the relative value of different interventions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Quality-adjusted life years (QALYs) combine length of life with quality of life on a scale from 0 (death) to 1 (perfect health).","QALYs are used in health economics to compare the cost-effectiveness of different healthcare interventions.","One QALY represents one year of life lived in perfect health."],"references":["Sarah J. Whitehead, Shehzad Ali, Health outcomes in economic evaluation: the QALY and utilities, British Medical Bulletin, Volume 96, Issue 1, December 2010, Pages 5\u201321, https://doi.org/10.1093/bmb/ldq033"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51695"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16673"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51695"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T15:50:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T21:24:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9364"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66246"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4948"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"positi